remarks: Listed as "Dendroceros cf. difficilis" by P.M.McCarthy, Checkl. Austral. Liverworts and Hornworts 35 (2003).
Fransén (2004: 90) recognises Australian material as subsp. hampei. Bartramia hampeana subsp. hampeana occurs in southern Africa.
Australian reports of B. halleriana belong here. Bell (2006: 253) cites a narrower global APC Dist. than Fransén (2004b: fig. 4).

Global APC Dist. given in Flora of Australia treatment (Bell 2006: 254) differs from that given by Fransén (2004a: fig. 16) and includes the distribution of Bartramia ithyphylla. Bartramia robusta is restricted to Australia, New Zealand, Tristan da Cunha, Crozet Is., and Kerguelen.

Spence & Ramsay (2006: 299) do not mention occurrence in the A.C.T., but there are dots on the A.C.T. on the APC Dist. map. Cocos Islands report based on D.G. Williams (CBG 8601807), identified by Spence & Ramsay (2005, in herb.).

Taxonomic status of this name is uncertain. Frahm (1996) recognised the variety Rhacocarpus rehmannianus var. webbianus. However, in the Flora of Southern Africa (Magill & Van Rooy 1998), Rhacocarpus rehmannianus is considered a synonym of Rhacocarpus purpurascens. Rhacocarpus webbianus most likely is also a synonym of Rhacocarpus purpurascens, but the type needs to be studied to confirm this.
If varieties are recognised in R. pennatum, Australian material belongs to var. aristatum.
All Australian material belongs to Forsstroemia trichomitria var. australis.
Australian material belongs to var. percaudatum.
Australian material belongs to var. rhizogemmae.
Australian mainland material belongs to Orthorrhynchium elegans subsp. cymbifolioides, while Lord Howe Island material belongs to subsp. nietneri.
All Australian material belongs to Garovaglia elegans subsp. dietrichiae.
All Australian material belongs to Garovaglia powellii subsp. muelleri var. muelleri.
The exact locality of the only Australian collection is uncertain (Reese & Stone, 1995: 14) and the collection was made long before the species was described.
All Australian material belongs to Fissidens bryoides var. schmidii.
Australian material belongs to G. pulvinata var. africana (Greven 2000: 220).
Australian material belongs to var. ambigua.
All Australian material belongs to Dawsonia superba var. pulchra (Wijk) Zanten

Smith (1971: 41) argues that Australian and New Zealand material should be treated as a distinct species, Polytrichadelphus innovans, limiting the APC Dist. of P. magellanicus to Juan Fernandez, southern Chile, the Fuegian region, the Falkland Islands and Tristan da Cunha. Hyvönen (2006: 137) prefers to treat all specimens from both sides of the Pacific as belonging to P. magellanicus. Qld and NSW reports not confirmed by Hyvönen (2006: 137).
Treated as Adelanthus falcatus (Hook.) Mitt. in Tas.
M.A.M.Renner & E.A.Brown, Fieldiana, Bot. 47: 169 (2008) indicate that the identity of the Australian material is in doubt.
Jungermannia monodon var. muelleri and Jungermannia monodon var. novaehollandiae are recognised as distinct taxa within Cupsidatula monodon , but no combinations presently exist.
Mastigobryum divaricatum var. muellerianum is recognised as a distinct taxon in Acromastigium divaricatum, but no combination presently exists.
See notes by M.Fulford, Brittonia 14: 128 (1962), for a discussion of the orthography of the name Lepidozia saddlensis.
Authorship of Colura leratii is sometimes cited as "(Steph.) Steph.", but Stephani published the name as a new taxon, without reference to a basionym.
As indicated by P.M.McCarthy, Cat. Austral. Liverworts & Hornworts 20 (2003), this taxon belongs in Cheilolejeunea, but no combination exists.
Aneura tasmanica Steph. is recognised as a distinct taxon in Tas.
Treated as Aneura graeffei Steph. in Tas.
Treated as Riccardia minima Carrington & Pearson in Tas.
Metzgeria decipiens is recognised as a distinct taxon in ACT.

G.A.M.Scott & D.C.Pike, Bryologist 91: 194–195 (1988), indicate that the spores from the AD isotype of Fossombronia dentata may represent Fossombronia pusilla var maritima (now F. maritima (Paton) Paton.

Fossombronia maritima (Paton) Paton is erroneously listed by P.M.McCarthy, Cat. Austral. Liverworts & Hornworts 40 (2003), as an illegitimate later homonym of F. maritima G.A.M.Scott & D.C.Pike (1987). However Scott & Pike's earlier name is invalid.
